According to https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/fd19/a13489d19b65e0cade68982ef28032d4d0c6.pdf, ‘désu’ has obligatory devoicing while ‘kásu’ has optional devoicing, which can only mean that vowel devoicing is lexically marked in Standard Japanese and thus phonemic. (That's what follows from the data in the article, even though the article itself doesn't let this have any consequences for its phonemic notation.) No matter how you analyse it, formulating a rule to cover all instances is not possible.
